00:14:25,680 --> 00:14:28,680
Just a little bit.
A dime, a nickel, a penny.

230
00:14:28,880 --> 00:14:31,320
Every bit helps.

231
00:14:32,200 --> 00:14:34,280
<i>The goal of the telethon that year...</i>

232
00:14:34,480 --> 00:14:38,600
<i>...was $3.9 million, which was
a lot of dough at that time.</i>

233
00:14:38,800 --> 00:14:42,400
Thank you, Tom.
You're a prince among men.

234
00:14:42,600 --> 00:14:44,960
Whoa, Lanny. There are
children watching!

235
00:14:45,200 --> 00:14:46,600
Where does he get his energy?

236
00:14:47,120 --> 00:14:48,520
<i>To remind viewers of the goal...</i>

237
00:14:48,720 --> 00:14:52,640
<i>...we agreed the telethon
could run 39 hours nonstop.</i>

238
00:14:53,680 --> 00:14:57,600
<i>The show would begin at 9 p. m. on
Friday and finish at noon on Sunday.</i>

239
00:14:57,800 --> 00:15:00,040
<i>We paced it so that
Vince and I were together...</i>

240
00:15:00,240 --> 00:15:02,240
<i>...for the kickoff,
most of the day Saturday...</i>

241
00:15:02,440 --> 00:15:05,800
<i>...then the big finale
on Sunday with us bleary-eyed...</i>

242
00:15:06,000 --> 00:15:08,800
<i>...and weeping as America
got ready to go to church.</i>

243
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:12,200
Lanny, Lanny. What are you doing?

244
00:15:12,400 --> 00:15:14,680
I'm ordering a pizza. I'm starving.

245
00:15:14,880 --> 00:15:18,440
No anchovies on mine, Lanny.
Hey, so who are you talking to?

246
00:15:18,640 --> 00:15:21,680
I'm talking to little Suzie
from Whittier, California...

247
00:15:21,880 --> 00:15:25,240
...and she is going to donate
three weeks of allowance.

248
00:15:25,440 --> 00:15:28,480
-How about that, folks?
-Suzie from Whittier, thank you.

249
00:15:28,680 --> 00:15:30,080
Three weeks of allowance.

250
00:15:30,320 --> 00:15:31,640
That's a challenge for all you-

251
00:15:31,840 --> 00:15:33,960
<i>What you have to understand
is that Vince and me...</i>

252
00:15:34,160 --> 00:15:36,240
<i>...were essentially a boy-girl act.</i>

253
00:15:36,440 --> 00:15:38,920
<i>I was the tramp,
ready for any sort of action...</i>

254
00:15:39,120 --> 00:15:40,640
<i>...and Vince was the gentleman...</i>

255
00:15:40,840 --> 00:15:42,880
<i>...always trying to make me
behave myself.</i>

256
00:15:43,080 --> 00:15:45,440
<i>I was pleasure, and he was control.</i>

257
00:15:45,800 --> 00:15:48,720
<i>I was rock 'n' roll,
and he was class.</i>

258
00:15:48,920 --> 00:15:53,080
<i>His presence gave America
permission to like me.</i>

259
00:15:55,440 --> 00:15:58,320
<i>My deal with the publisher
gave me first-class travel...</i>

260
00:15:58,520 --> 00:16:00,000
<i>...a luxury I'd never enjoyed.</i>

261
00:16:00,200 --> 00:16:02,480
Is there any chance of switching
to a window seat?

262
00:16:02,680 --> 00:16:04,840
Sorry, we're completely booked
in first.

263
00:16:05,040 --> 00:16:07,920
But these center seats
are really wonderful. See...

264
00:16:08,080 --> 00:16:10,120
...if you push here-
Can I show you?

265
00:16:10,320 --> 00:16:12,000
Sure.

266
00:16:13,640 --> 00:16:16,160
The chair swivels
to the left and the right.

267
00:16:16,360 --> 00:16:18,560
And this converts
to a full-sized dining table...

268
00:16:18,760 --> 00:16:20,440
...during our
Pan Am platinum service...

269
00:16:20,640 --> 00:16:23,080
...with damask linen
and silverware by Fornari...

270
00:16:23,280 --> 00:16:25,440
...so you don't have to eat off a tray.

271
00:16:25,640 --> 00:16:28,200
Again, that's only
for these center seats.

272
00:16:29,120 --> 00:16:30,360
How does that sound?

273
00:16:30,720 --> 00:16:33,240
<i>At that time, when you
traveled first class...</i>

274
00:16:33,440 --> 00:16:37,360
<i>...people would always ask you if you
met someone famous on the flight.</i>

275
00:16:37,560 --> 00:16:39,440
-Mr. Morris.
-Thank you.

276
00:16:39,600 --> 00:16:40,720
You're welcome.

277
00:16:49,920 --> 00:16:54,080
<i>Though he would later accuse me
of engineering this, I didn't.</i>

278
00:16:54,280 --> 00:16:55,560
<i>It just...</i>

279
00:16:55,760 --> 00:16:57,400
<i>...happened.</i>

280
00:17:03,440 --> 00:17:06,400
Reuben. So they-
They record these songs...

281
00:17:06,600 --> 00:17:08,240
...in a studio that I am paying for.

282
00:17:08,440 --> 00:17:10,200
Songs that are recorded for me...

283
00:17:10,400 --> 00:17:12,040
...that they are
contracted to provide.

284
00:17:12,240 --> 00:17:14,120
-Are you with me here?
-Yes, it's just that-

285
00:17:14,320 --> 00:17:17,360
No, it's just that nothing, Irv.
Please, let me finish. They record...

286
00:17:17,560 --> 00:17:20,880
<i>I read an interview where Lanny was
given credit for insisting his butler...</i>

287
00:17:21,040 --> 00:17:24,760
<i>...travel in the same class and stay
at the same hotels as his boss.</i>

288
00:17:25,360 --> 00:17:28,600
<i>The valet's attentiveness
was impressive.</i>

289
00:17:29,520 --> 00:17:32,720
Looks like you'll be having
dinner with Lanny Morris.

290
00:17:35,680 --> 00:17:38,280
-Hello.
-Hi.

291
00:17:48,200 --> 00:17:50,880
We should get a waiter to slide
a matchbook under the airplane.

292
00:17:52,000 --> 00:17:53,480
There we go.

293
00:17:53,680 --> 00:17:55,320
That should hold.

294
00:17:56,800 --> 00:17:57,960
This is my friend Reuben.

295
00:17:58,160 --> 00:17:59,320
-Hi.
-Hi.

296
00:17:59,520 --> 00:18:01,960
And this is also my friend,
technically speaking...

297
00:18:02,160 --> 00:18:04,080
-... and business manager, Irv.
-Hi.

298
00:18:06,160 --> 00:18:07,400
My name is Lanny.

299
00:18:11,960 --> 00:18:13,480
And what's your name?

300
00:18:14,880 --> 00:18:16,960
Bonnie. Bonnie Trout.

301
00:18:17,160 --> 00:18:18,440
What do you do, Bonnie?

302
00:18:18,720 --> 00:18:20,120
I teach.

303
00:18:20,320 --> 00:18:21,880
And what do you teach?

304
00:18:22,080 --> 00:18:24,200
-Second grade.
-Well, we have a lot in common.

305
00:18:24,400 --> 00:18:26,800
You teach second grade,
I went to second grade.

306
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:30,040
-Irv, you went to second grade too?
-Many times.

307
00:18:30,240 --> 00:18:31,640
Tell me, Miss Trout-

308
00:18:31,840 --> 00:18:33,200
I don't mean to be impolite...

309
00:18:33,400 --> 00:18:34,920
...but I was wondering...

310
00:18:35,120 --> 00:18:38,520
...how a second-grade schoolteacher
affords to fly first class.

311
00:18:40,560 --> 00:18:42,680
Well, I have a pass...

312
00:18:42,880 --> 00:18:46,200
...that allows me free use
of the subway on weekends...

313
00:18:46,400 --> 00:18:49,440
...and the hot lunches
at school are only 50 cents.

314
00:18:50,800 --> 00:18:53,120
And I'm the mistress...

315
00:18:53,320 --> 00:18:54,720
...of a wealthy married man...

316
00:18:54,920 --> 00:18:57,440
...and when he and his wife
go on vacation, he treats me...

317
00:18:57,640 --> 00:19:00,680
...to a first-class trip
in the opposite direction.

318
00:19:01,480 --> 00:19:05,720
But look at me, talking only about
myself. What do you do for a living?

319
00:19:07,040 --> 00:19:09,440
I'm a French impressionist
painter out of Tahiti, mainly.

320
00:19:09,640 --> 00:19:11,960
I'm doing that to pay the bills.
My ambition is to be...

321
00:19:12,160 --> 00:19:14,120
...a stockbroker in Paris.

322
00:19:14,440 --> 00:19:16,000
-I don't get it.
-Paul Gauguin.

323
00:19:16,200 --> 00:19:18,080
He gave up being
a successful stockbroker...

324
00:19:18,280 --> 00:19:20,600
...to become a painter
in the South Seas.

325
00:19:21,560 --> 00:19:23,360
You think the average
person knows that?

326
00:19:23,560 --> 00:19:26,760
Well, we're not talking about
the average person, Irv.

327
00:19:29,800 --> 00:19:31,200
<i>In some ways...</i>

328
00:19:31,400 --> 00:19:34,440
<i>...he had never stopped
being a hero to me.</i>

329
00:19:35,280 --> 00:19:39,240
<i>That's why it was impossible
to think he might also be a killer.</i>

330
00:19:45,680 --> 00:19:47,160
Well, this has been great.

331
00:19:47,360 --> 00:19:49,400
I'm gonna see you
inside your apartment.

332
00:19:49,600 --> 00:19:51,960
-There's really no need.
-Don't be silly.

333
00:19:52,160 --> 00:19:53,920
I'm not gonna try to come in.

334
00:19:54,120 --> 00:19:55,560
Promise.

335
00:19:56,320 --> 00:19:58,800
You've been away from your
apartment for how long now?

336
00:19:59,000 --> 00:20:00,600
-Ages.
-You never know if somebody's...

337
00:20:00,800 --> 00:20:02,320
...broken in while you were gone.

338
00:20:02,520 --> 00:20:05,080
I'll just see you inside your door.

339
00:20:05,760 --> 00:20:08,520
Believe me, I'm-
I'm not trying to seduce you.

340
00:20:08,720 --> 00:20:10,600
<i>I have to do the Today show
at 7 a. m.</i>

341
00:20:10,800 --> 00:20:13,080
They want me in Makeup at 6:15.

342
00:20:13,280 --> 00:20:15,440
<i>Bonnie had moved to New York
for the teaching job...</i>

343
00:20:15,640 --> 00:20:17,520
<i>...a little over a year ago.</i>

344
00:20:17,720 --> 00:20:21,600
<i>I had never visited her and had
no idea if this was the right place.</i>

345
00:20:22,800 --> 00:20:24,200
Which floor?

346
00:20:24,760 --> 00:20:26,560
Why...

347
00:20:27,640 --> 00:20:28,840
-Four-D.
-Forty?

348
00:20:29,360 --> 00:20:31,120
It only goes up to six.

349
00:20:33,520 --> 00:20:35,040
Four-D-

350
00:20:35,240 --> 00:20:37,360
Four-D, the fourth floor.

351
00:20:59,440 --> 00:21:00,680
Which way?

352
00:21:01,680 --> 00:21:03,400
-Guess.
-Why?

353
00:21:03,600 --> 00:21:04,800
It's a test.

354
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:06,440
A test?

355
00:21:08,160 --> 00:21:09,680
Okay.

356
00:21:09,880 --> 00:21:11,240
This way.

357
00:21:14,720 --> 00:21:16,840
So why didn't we take this elevator?

358
00:21:17,040 --> 00:21:18,600
Doesn't work.

359
00:21:21,720 --> 00:21:23,120
Well...

360
00:21:23,920 --> 00:21:25,240
...good night.

361
00:21:25,440 --> 00:21:27,320
No, I'm going to see you
into your apartment.

362
00:21:27,520 --> 00:21:29,920
And then I'm gonna leave you
alone until tomorrow.

363
00:21:46,600 --> 00:21:49,240
I never get which key goes in
which lock the first time.

364
00:21:51,680 --> 00:21:53,880
Hey, looks like they fixed it.

365
00:22:04,800 --> 00:22:06,200
You okay?

366
00:22:06,400 --> 00:22:08,720
Maybe we should turn on a light.

367
00:22:21,880 --> 00:22:23,160
Well...

368
00:22:24,280 --> 00:22:25,760
I'm going to leave you now.

369
00:22:26,000 --> 00:22:29,160
I have Reuben and Irv waiting
in the limousine downstairs...

370
00:22:29,600 --> 00:22:32,440
<i>...and I should get some sleep
for the Today show.</i>

371
00:22:34,600 --> 00:22:35,960
So...

372
00:22:40,560 --> 00:22:42,680
It was lovely to meet you, Bonnie.

373
00:23:01,320 --> 00:23:03,520
<i>By the end of the telethon,
we had no voices.</i>

374
00:23:03,720 --> 00:23:07,160
<i>Thirty-nine hours
of nonstop entertainment.</i>

375
00:23:07,360 --> 00:23:10,080
<i>A telethon was a superhuman feat.</i>

376
00:23:10,280 --> 00:23:13,600
<i>We weren't just heroes,
we were gods.</i>

377
00:23:16,280 --> 00:23:18,960
<i>A couple of the boys were there
to make sure we got out alive...</i>

378
00:23:19,160 --> 00:23:21,400
<i>...to make the flight to New York.</i>

379
00:23:25,120 --> 00:23:27,920
Everyone. Listen. Listen.

380
00:23:28,120 --> 00:23:30,120
Gentlemen. Gentlemen, please.

381
00:23:30,520 --> 00:23:33,440
Gentlemen, if I could just
have your attention.

382
00:23:33,800 --> 00:23:35,560
Everyone, Mr. Collins
and Mr. Morris...

383
00:23:35,760 --> 00:23:37,920
...will answer questions
at the press conference...

384
00:23:38,120 --> 00:23:39,720
...at the Palace Del Sol.

385
00:23:39,920 --> 00:23:41,840
Gentlemen, there will be
plenty of time...

386
00:23:42,000 --> 00:23:45,320
...to answer your questions
at the Palace Del Sol.

387
00:23:45,520 --> 00:23:48,480
Thank you, we will answer your
questions at the press conference.

388
00:23:48,680 --> 00:23:50,560
Thank you for coming.

389
00:23:56,320 --> 00:23:59,200
<i>We had a full police escort, along
with bodyguards who were there...</i>

390
00:23:59,400 --> 00:24:02,160
<i>...to protect us from any thoughts
we might have of going AWOL...</i>

391
00:24:02,360 --> 00:24:04,040
<i>...prior to this press conference.</i>

392
00:24:04,240 --> 00:24:07,240
<i>A pair of New Jersey's finest
walked on either side of us...</i>

393
00:24:07,440 --> 00:24:09,920
<i>...as we entered
the lobby of the hotel.</i>

394
00:24:10,120 --> 00:24:12,720
<i>It was an indication of how
legitimate the Mob had gone...</i>

395
00:24:12,920 --> 00:24:15,040
<i>...that they could
bring in the local police...</i>

396
00:24:15,240 --> 00:24:17,600
<i>...to guard the façade of their racket.</i>

397
00:24:18,160 --> 00:24:22,120
<i>The local chief was a man
named Jack Scaglia.</i>

398
00:24:22,320 --> 00:24:25,080
And of course, the two
gentlemen on my right...

399
00:24:25,280 --> 00:24:28,440
...who need no introduction,
have come here directly...

400
00:24:28,640 --> 00:24:32,160
...from their record-breaking
polio telethon in Miami, Florida.

401
00:24:33,200 --> 00:24:36,480
So the first thing I'd like to announce
is that Mr. Sanmarco...

402
00:24:36,960 --> 00:24:38,160
<i>I wish I could tell you...</i>

403
00:24:38,360 --> 00:24:40,840
<i>...that Sally Sanmarco
was a slim, 6-foot-6 guy...</i>

404
00:24:41,040 --> 00:24:43,880
<i>...who looked like a prince
and spoke with an English accent.</i>

405
00:24:44,080 --> 00:24:46,360
<i>Then I wouldn't be
falling back on the stereotype.</i>

406
00:24:46,640 --> 00:24:50,080
<i>The trouble was, Sally was
straight out of central casting.</i>

407
00:24:50,880 --> 00:24:52,800
<i>A gangster
who looked and talked...</i>

408
00:24:53,040 --> 00:24:55,560
<i>...just like you would expect
from the movies.</i>

409
00:24:55,760 --> 00:24:58,240
How did it feel to raise
all that money for polio?

410
00:24:58,760 --> 00:25:00,840
It felt great. It felt really great.

411
00:25:01,040 --> 00:25:03,800
<i>From a publicity angle, and in
terms of giving him legitimacy...</i>

412
00:25:04,000 --> 00:25:06,120
<i>...this was a huge coup for Sally.</i>

413
00:25:06,320 --> 00:25:08,720
<i>Like I said, we were gods.</i>

414
00:25:09,960 --> 00:25:13,400
<i>We'd only been in the New York area
for an hour or so, during which time...</i>

415
00:25:13,600 --> 00:25:16,240
<i>...we were constantly watched
by police and reporters...</i>

416
00:25:16,440 --> 00:25:19,080
<i>...which ended up being
a good thing for us.</i>

417
00:25:19,280 --> 00:25:21,600
We got you our best bridal suite.

418
00:25:22,080 --> 00:25:24,000
Fucking nice, huh?

419
00:25:25,080 --> 00:25:27,680
People talk about having fancy
apartments and hotel rooms...

420
00:25:27,880 --> 00:25:29,880
...on the West Side of Manhattan.
What do they see?

421
00:25:30,080 --> 00:25:33,120
Fucking New Jersey.
Here, you see New York City.

422
00:25:40,080 --> 00:25:42,400
<i>Unfortunately,
Vince and I were acquainted...</i>

423
00:25:42,600 --> 00:25:46,720
<i>...with the dead girl in the bathroom
of our hotel suite in New Jersey.</i>

424
00:25:47,240 --> 00:25:50,320
<i>Her last name was O'Flaherty.</i>

425
00:25:50,760 --> 00:25:53,760
<i>Her first name was Maureen.</i>

426
00:25:54,000 --> 00:25:57,480
<i>Karen, we decided to trade
apartments, not identities.</i>

427
00:25:57,680 --> 00:25:59,160
<i>Why didn't you make up a name?</i>

428
00:25:59,360 --> 00:26:01,760
Bonnie, I was looking
at a five-hour flight.

429
00:26:02,000 --> 00:26:05,000
I didn't wanna make up a life story
that wasn't attached to anything.

430
00:26:05,200 --> 00:26:08,520
Well, I returned the offense.
I got to pretend I was you.

431
00:26:08,720 --> 00:26:10,240
<i>-What?
-You received a package.</i>

432
00:26:10,440 --> 00:26:12,640
Messenger service.
I signed your name.

433
00:26:12,840 --> 00:26:15,360
-Who's it from?
-No address. Want me to open it?

434
00:26:15,560 --> 00:26:17,000
-Sure.
-That's good. I already did.

435
00:26:17,200 --> 00:26:18,440
It's a manuscript.

436
00:26:18,640 --> 00:26:20,960
"Excerpt From the Memoirs of...

437
00:26:21,160 --> 00:26:22,840
...Lanny Morris. "

438
00:26:23,040 --> 00:26:26,880
Hey, all your dreams are coming true.
He's writing you love letters already.

439
00:26:27,080 --> 00:26:28,960
Bonnie, I need
to know what he's written.

440
00:26:29,160 --> 00:26:32,960
-Well, I'll send it to you.
-Now. Before he calls me tomorrow.

441
00:26:35,120 --> 00:26:37,920
-Please?
-All right.

442
00:26:39,280 --> 00:26:41,000
All right.

443
00:26:41,200 --> 00:26:42,600
Here we go.

444
00:26:44,880 --> 00:26:48,640
"Let me explain to you why two
very famous guys just finishing...

445
00:26:48,840 --> 00:26:52,800
...a nationally broadcast telethon
ended up in New Jersey. "

446
00:26:57,240 --> 00:27:02,240
<i>For years, the Palace Del Sol was
one of the centers of Mob prosperity.</i>

447
00:27:02,440 --> 00:27:05,280
<i>Needless to say, a major
headliner in the showroom...</i>

448
00:27:05,520 --> 00:27:08,520
<i>...helped legitimize
the entire operation.</i>

449
00:27:08,720 --> 00:27:10,400
Give her a kiss. Yeah, beautiful.

450
00:27:10,600 --> 00:27:13,480
One more, guys. That's it.
That's great. Thank you.

451
00:27:13,680 --> 00:27:16,040
<i>Vince and I needed help
in keeping us up all the time...</i>

452
00:27:16,240 --> 00:27:18,320
<i>...and in the way of thinking
in the '50s...</i>

453
00:27:18,520 --> 00:27:20,680
<i>...anything you didn't take
with a needle was okay.</i>

454
00:27:20,880 --> 00:27:24,360
<i>It wasn't "serious" serious.
It was like running a red light.</i>

455
00:27:24,560 --> 00:27:29,240
<i>Everyone used bennies. Vince added
them to his morning coffee like sugar.</i>

456
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:36,000
<i>Not that you could tell.</i>

457
00:27:37,720 --> 00:27:39,640
<i>When we did finally
decide to flatten out...</i>

458
00:27:39,840 --> 00:27:43,640
<i>...we'd take two or three Tuinals,
or three or four "Threeinals. "</i>

