We've really just leased
an oil well called Vince Collins...

689
00:42:56,200 --> 00:42:59,400
...and granted Ms. O'Connor
the right to tap.

690
00:42:59,600 --> 00:43:02,920
I think we have a responsibility to...

691
00:43:03,400 --> 00:43:05,600
...monitor the drilling.

692
00:43:27,880 --> 00:43:30,240
-Hello.
-Mrs. O'Flaherty?

693
00:43:30,840 --> 00:43:32,280
Yes.

694
00:43:32,520 --> 00:43:36,000
My name's O'Connor.
I'm the one writing the book.

695
00:43:48,560 --> 00:43:51,640
The book will be
centered around Vince Collins.

696
00:43:51,840 --> 00:43:54,560
I'll be asking him a lot of questions.

697
00:43:54,760 --> 00:43:59,560
I wanted to know if there were any
you'd like to have answered yourself.

698
00:44:03,320 --> 00:44:07,680
Maureen and I planted this tree
on her fifth birthday.

699
00:44:09,080 --> 00:44:12,360
Father did most of the digging,
of course.

700
00:44:13,400 --> 00:44:15,480
She'd be 38.

701
00:44:16,320 --> 00:44:19,200
I'm 59 myself.

702
00:44:21,440 --> 00:44:23,880
If she were alive now...

703
00:44:25,240 --> 00:44:28,640
...we'd be talking about things,
back and forth...

704
00:44:28,880 --> 00:44:30,600
...like two women.

705
00:44:31,240 --> 00:44:33,480
Like you and I are doing.

706
00:44:38,880 --> 00:44:41,000
And Maureen's father?

707
00:44:41,960 --> 00:44:44,360
Frank died six years ago.

708
00:44:45,000 --> 00:44:47,040
He took his own life.

709
00:44:47,600 --> 00:44:50,560
One night, just before he died...

710
00:44:50,760 --> 00:44:53,760
...he dug up the earth
around this tree...

711
00:44:54,240 --> 00:44:56,920
...he took the urn
with Maureen's ashes in it...

712
00:44:57,120 --> 00:44:59,720
...and spread them around its roots.

713
00:45:01,560 --> 00:45:05,160
So this is my daughter.

714
00:45:06,760 --> 00:45:09,240
This is what I have of her.

715
00:45:15,920 --> 00:45:18,560
<i>-Are you Catholic?
-My- My mother was.</i>

716
00:45:19,280 --> 00:45:21,720
<i>Then you will understand
my dilemma.</i>

717
00:45:21,920 --> 00:45:25,480
<i>Our faith offers an afterlife.</i>

718
00:45:26,640 --> 00:45:28,840
A daughter needs her mother.

719
00:45:29,920 --> 00:45:35,680
So I have to live out this life
as far from sin as I can manage.

720
00:45:38,480 --> 00:45:41,000
<i>I'll never see my husband again.</i>

721
00:45:41,520 --> 00:45:43,840
<i>He's consigned himself to hell.</i>

722
00:45:46,160 --> 00:45:49,480
<i>But what if Maureen
killed herself too?</i>

723
00:45:53,040 --> 00:45:55,560
She's in hell, with my husband.

724
00:45:55,760 --> 00:45:59,720
The life I'm trying to lead
will bring me to heaven's grace...

725
00:46:00,760 --> 00:46:04,000
...only to hear
their screams of torment.

726
00:46:05,480 --> 00:46:07,600
<i>Chief Scaglia,
you were in the hotel room...</i>

727
00:46:07,800 --> 00:46:10,840
<i>...when they found
Maureen's body in the tub.</i>

728
00:46:11,280 --> 00:46:15,000
So was Sally, so was Lanny,
so was Vince.

729
00:46:16,400 --> 00:46:20,400
And there was also
a PR lady there from the hotel.

730
00:46:20,800 --> 00:46:22,280
How do you think she died?

731
00:46:22,960 --> 00:46:25,880
She died in an auto accident
two weeks later. It was terrible.

732
00:46:29,200 --> 00:46:30,360
No, Maureen.

733
00:46:30,560 --> 00:46:33,120
-How did Maureen die?
-She drowned.

734
00:46:33,320 --> 00:46:35,040
-Why?
-What do you mean, why?

735
00:46:35,240 --> 00:46:37,640
You and I take baths all the time.
We don't drown in them.

736
00:46:37,840 --> 00:46:40,760
You and I do not mix
sleeping pills with booze.

737
00:46:40,960 --> 00:46:43,760
-She committed suicide?
-Overdose is the official story.

738
00:46:43,960 --> 00:46:47,640
What's the official story on the fact
that the staff of the hotel in Miami...

739
00:46:47,840 --> 00:46:50,760
<i>...all seemed to know she delivered
room service to the boys' suite...</i>

740
00:46:50,960 --> 00:46:53,680
...three days before
and was never seen alive again?

741
00:46:53,880 --> 00:46:55,160
What happened to her?

742
00:46:55,360 --> 00:46:57,720
How did she end up
in a hotel room in New Jersey?

743
00:46:57,920 --> 00:47:01,640
Sally never had any problem
moving girls around. Okay?

744
00:47:01,840 --> 00:47:02,960
He had two hotels.

745
00:47:03,160 --> 00:47:05,080
-So Sally arranged it?
-No, I don't think so.

746
00:47:05,280 --> 00:47:08,040
You see, she was brought up there
as a reward for the boys...

747
00:47:08,240 --> 00:47:10,760
...and I think she started
to party just a little too early.

748
00:47:10,960 --> 00:47:13,360
She was a student.
This was a summer job.

749
00:47:13,560 --> 00:47:14,760
Listen to me...

750
00:47:15,200 --> 00:47:20,880
...the Palace Del Sol was very
important to Sally, okay?

751
00:47:21,080 --> 00:47:24,120
He launched his new wing...

752
00:47:24,320 --> 00:47:27,480
...with a push
from Lanny and Vince...

753
00:47:27,680 --> 00:47:33,080
...and this stupid girl
shows up dead.

754
00:47:33,360 --> 00:47:37,720
She's not gonna come back.
We do the best thing for all of us.

755
00:47:37,920 --> 00:47:42,200
We speed up the investigation
and we cremate her. Okay?

756
00:47:42,400 --> 00:47:44,520
End of story.

757
00:47:47,200 --> 00:47:50,640
-Here you are.
-Here's your lobster.

758
00:47:50,840 --> 00:47:53,640
-Enjoy.
-Looks great.

759
00:47:55,040 --> 00:47:58,640
"Sally said, 'I'll have them send you
up your own shipment of lobsters.

760
00:47:58,840 --> 00:48:00,800
<i>You like lobster?"'</i>

761
00:48:01,360 --> 00:48:04,520
<i>We said we did
because we really did.</i>

762
00:48:05,240 --> 00:48:08,040
<i>You shouldn't have done that,
Stanley. I don't eat lobster.</i>

763
00:48:10,840 --> 00:48:13,160
<i>Were there any signs of violence
on her body?</i>

764
00:48:13,360 --> 00:48:17,480
No, no. There were some
small scratches on the torso.

765
00:48:19,280 --> 00:48:24,440
<i>Why did my daughter die?
Did she kill herself?</i>

766
00:48:25,320 --> 00:48:28,720
<i>What had they done to her
that would make her do that?</i>

767
00:48:31,240 --> 00:48:33,360
<i>What had they done?</i>

768
00:48:38,120 --> 00:48:40,280
<i>Once upon a time...</i>

769
00:48:40,480 --> 00:48:44,000
<i>...when terrible things
happened to people...</i>

770
00:48:44,200 --> 00:48:46,640
<i>...they were left as a mystery.</i>

771
00:48:48,720 --> 00:48:51,840
<i>Even the tabloids kept a distance.</i>

772
00:48:57,040 --> 00:49:02,560
<i>Some things were allowed
to be left just the way they were.</i>

773
00:49:11,000 --> 00:49:12,760
Any trouble with the directions
I gave you?

774
00:49:12,960 --> 00:49:16,240
-Only the parts where I had to turn.
-Sorry.

775
00:49:17,120 --> 00:49:19,400
It's the price of seclusion.

776
00:49:24,280 --> 00:49:26,200
You haven't switched over
to cassette?

777
00:49:26,400 --> 00:49:30,120
-Actually, it's my dad's.
-And what does he do?

778
00:49:31,440 --> 00:49:33,480
He was a journalist too.

779
00:49:34,480 --> 00:49:36,720
He did a big story on you once.

780
00:49:36,920 --> 00:49:39,480
Followed a little girl who had polio.

781
00:49:39,800 --> 00:49:41,960
You took her under your wing...

782
00:49:43,080 --> 00:49:45,320
...and now she's interviewing you.

783
00:49:48,720 --> 00:49:51,840
He must be proud that his daughter's
making such a name for herself.

784
00:49:52,360 --> 00:49:54,360
I'd like to think so.

785
00:49:55,520 --> 00:49:58,960
-He died last year.
-Sorry to hear that.

786
00:50:00,560 --> 00:50:04,040
-Would you like some coffee?
-Sure.

787
00:50:10,800 --> 00:50:12,600
Are you alone here?

788
00:50:12,800 --> 00:50:16,640
Yes. The thought of having live-in help
is a little poisonous to me.

789
00:50:16,880 --> 00:50:18,200
Why's that?

790
00:50:18,400 --> 00:50:20,200
Well, I'd have to talk to them...

791
00:50:20,400 --> 00:50:22,760
...ask them how
their family was doing...

792
00:50:22,960 --> 00:50:25,480
...hear about this and that,
introduce them to the guests...

793
00:50:25,680 --> 00:50:28,200
...and tell them
how their family was doing.

794
00:50:28,400 --> 00:50:31,960
All so that I would
seem to be a nice guy...

795
00:50:32,160 --> 00:50:33,680
...which is an awful lot of work...

796
00:50:33,880 --> 00:50:36,200
...considering what I cherish
most in life these days...

797
00:50:36,400 --> 00:50:38,400
...is not to have to be Vince Collins.

798
00:50:38,600 --> 00:50:39,960
No Reuben in your life?

799
00:50:41,200 --> 00:50:43,120
How do you know about Reuben?

800
00:50:43,480 --> 00:50:46,880
He was in a lot of the material
I've been looking at.

801
00:50:47,080 --> 00:50:48,480
No, I never had a Reuben.

802
00:50:48,680 --> 00:50:50,920
Lanny always paid him directly.
He was Lanny's man.

803
00:50:51,120 --> 00:50:52,520
Right.

804
00:50:54,840 --> 00:50:56,800
You know, what I like is to...

805
00:50:57,040 --> 00:50:58,560
...read...

806
00:50:59,600 --> 00:51:00,960
...think.

807
00:51:01,160 --> 00:51:03,240
It's to have the freedom...

808
00:51:03,440 --> 00:51:05,840
...to get up and leave
without telling anyone about it...

809
00:51:06,040 --> 00:51:07,880
...any time of day.

810
00:51:09,800 --> 00:51:12,040
Or even having to say goodbye.

811
00:51:14,160 --> 00:51:17,920
To be backstage, surrounded
by acrobats, actors, magicians...

812
00:51:18,160 --> 00:51:19,920
...it was intoxicating.

813
00:51:20,120 --> 00:51:21,880
You know, I was only 12 years old.

814
00:51:22,080 --> 00:51:23,640
That's a...

815
00:51:23,840 --> 00:51:25,280
That's a pretty impressionable age.

816
00:51:25,520 --> 00:51:28,440
<i>-To hear all these stories of touring...
-My father always told me...</i>

817
00:51:28,640 --> 00:51:32,000
<i>...that nothing had meaning
unless it could be put on the record.</i>

818
00:51:33,400 --> 00:51:35,360
<i>Yet things had changed.</i>

819
00:51:36,440 --> 00:51:38,440
<i>As Vince had pointed out
at our first meeting...</i>

820
00:51:38,640 --> 00:51:42,760
<i>...it had become fashionable
to put yourself into the story.</i>

821
00:51:43,440 --> 00:51:46,600
<i>The question became
how far you were prepared to go.</i>

822
00:52:08,960 --> 00:52:13,120
-Excuse me. That's not mine.
-Oh, I'm sorry.

823
00:52:15,920 --> 00:52:18,040
Aren't you Miss Trout?

824
00:52:18,240 --> 00:52:20,760
We've met,
on the plane to New York.

825
00:52:20,960 --> 00:52:22,120
-Reuben.
-Excuse me, sir.

826
00:52:22,320 --> 00:52:24,960
Can I leave you
for just a second, please?

827
00:52:28,560 --> 00:52:31,200
I'm so deeply sorry, Miss Trout,
the way you were treated.

828
00:52:31,400 --> 00:52:35,240
-He could have left a note.
-Of course.

829
00:52:36,480 --> 00:52:39,880
Miss Trout, I would like you
to understand something.

830
00:52:40,720 --> 00:52:45,240
I have a great loyalty to Mr. Morris.
He's treated me very well.

831
00:52:45,440 --> 00:52:47,080
I'm very grateful.

832
00:52:48,400 --> 00:52:51,320
He has done wonderful things
for many people...

833
00:52:51,520 --> 00:52:56,280
...and I have been privileged
to work for him.

834
00:52:57,800 --> 00:53:00,000
But I do have certain principles...

835
00:53:00,200 --> 00:53:04,240
...especially about how women
are to be treated and respected.

836
00:53:04,640 --> 00:53:09,800
Mr. Morris can be very attentive,
but once he has a woman...

837
00:53:10,960 --> 00:53:13,640
Oh, God, I think
it's almost a sickness.

838
00:53:15,560 --> 00:53:17,320
When he left you that morning...

839
00:53:17,520 --> 00:53:20,040
...you may have felt bad,
but believe me, Miss Trout...

840
00:53:20,200 --> 00:53:21,960
...to have him out of your life...

841
00:53:22,160 --> 00:53:24,760
...is the best thing that
could have happened to you.

842
00:53:25,800 --> 00:53:29,320
At that point, you may have felt
your life was wounded.

843
00:53:30,760 --> 00:53:32,520
It wasn't.

844
00:53:33,360 --> 00:53:34,600
It was saved.

845
00:53:43,320 --> 00:53:45,600
<i>Vince, I was very clear about this
from the beginning.</i>

846
00:53:45,800 --> 00:53:47,320
<i>I'm not out to play games with you.</i>

847
00:53:47,520 --> 00:53:49,800
<i>This is why you're being paid
a huge amount of money.</i>

848
00:53:50,760 --> 00:53:52,520
<i>This isn't entirely about money,
you know.</i>

849
00:53:52,720 --> 00:53:55,160
A million dollars is more than
the gross of your last film.

850
00:53:56,400 --> 00:53:58,600
I was somehow
under the impression that my life...

851
00:53:58,800 --> 00:54:01,640
...might have been of more than
passing interest.

852
00:54:01,840 --> 00:54:04,680
But if my fleeting encounter with
a girl named Maureen O'Flaherty...

853
00:54:04,880 --> 00:54:07,720
...is all you really want to talk about,
then that's what we'll do.

854
00:54:09,160 --> 00:54:11,360
I have to make an appearance
at the clinic tomorrow.

855
00:54:11,560 --> 00:54:13,600
We can come back
and talk after that.

856
00:54:14,600 --> 00:54:16,240
It's Wonderland.

857
00:54:16,440 --> 00:54:17,960
I imagine you might remember that.

858
00:54:31,600 --> 00:54:35,560
<i>He was right.
I did remember Wonderland.</i>

859
00:54:36,400 --> 00:54:38,040
-You ready?
-Ready.

860
00:54:38,240 --> 00:54:43,280
<i>When I was a girl, the entire hospital
was devoted to children with polio.</i>

861
00:54:44,880 --> 00:54:47,960
<i>Since that time,
it had become a clinic for kids...</i>

862
00:54:48,160 --> 00:54:51,240
<i>...with a variety of different
physical handicaps.</i>

863
00:54:54,720 --> 00:54:57,960
<i>Once a year, the children
would put on a pageant...</i>

864
00:54:58,120 --> 00:55:01,320
<i>...playing different characters
from Alice in Wonderland.</i>

865
00:55:02,320 --> 00:55:04,640
<i>Vince, in his continuing support
of the hospital...</i>

866
00:55:04,840 --> 00:55:07,200
<i>...had hired a band and a singer.</i>

867
00:55:14,400 --> 00:55:16,040
Who is that?

868
00:55:16,240 --> 00:55:19,880
I don't know.
She's good, whoever she is.

869
00:55:30,880 --> 00:55:33,960
Karen, do you mind if we start
this conversation tomorrow?

870
00:55:34,160 --> 00:55:37,640
I'm just...
I'm not feeling all that well.

871
00:55:38,320 --> 00:55:39,720
-Vince-
-In fact, it won't make...

872
00:55:39,920 --> 00:55:42,120
...any difference over there.
The office is closed.

873
00:55:42,280 --> 00:55:43,440
They've been working late.

874
00:55:43,640 --> 00:55:45,560
Then they've been working
much too hard.

875
00:55:46,840 --> 00:55:49,360
First thing tomorrow. First thing.

876
00:55:56,080 --> 00:55:58,360
I hope your editors were reasonable.

877
00:55:58,560 --> 00:56:01,400
Reasonable? No, they weren't.

878
00:56:01,600 --> 00:56:03,560
We can go as late as you like.

879
00:56:03,760 --> 00:56:05,000
That's good.

880
00:56:05,200 --> 00:56:06,560
It might take us
into the evening.

881
00:56:06,760 --> 00:56:08,640
I had a feeling
that might be the case.

882
00:56:09,120 --> 00:56:11,680
So I've ordered a hot and cold
smorgasbord to be brought in.

883
00:56:11,880 --> 00:56:13,280
We can work through dinner.

884
00:56:13,480 --> 00:56:15,560
-We'll be having company?
-Yes.

885
00:56:17,000 --> 00:56:18,440
I have...

886
00:56:18,640 --> 00:56:20,280
...a surprise for you.

887
00:56:21,200 --> 00:56:23,840
Actually, this is a fairly big deal
for me as well.

888
00:56:25,000 --> 00:56:27,280
I've asked Lanny to join us today.

889
00:56:28,520 --> 00:56:29,520
Lanny?

890
00:56:30,840 --> 00:56:32,880
Well, this is something.

891
00:56:33,720 --> 00:56:36,640
Neuman and Newberry will certainly
be getting their money's worth.

892
00:56:37,160 --> 00:56:39,400
I thought that if I was
going to discuss something...

893
00:56:39,600 --> 00:56:41,320
...that had such an impact
on our lives...

894
00:56:41,520 --> 00:56:44,000
...it would be fair for Lanny
to hear what I had to say.

895
00:56:44,680 --> 00:56:46,280
Given that we've
never talked about it.

896
00:56:46,480 --> 00:56:49,040
I'm sure I'll have lots to ask him.
When is he coming?

897
00:56:49,240 --> 00:56:51,080
He should be here any minute now.

898
00:56:51,640 --> 00:56:53,400
This is very exciting.

899
00:56:53,960 --> 00:56:55,680
Shit.

900
00:57:09,720 --> 00:57:11,880
<i>-Yes?
-Bonnie, I have to talk fast.</i>

901
00:57:12,080 --> 00:57:15,000
I need you to do exactly as I tell you
and I can't tell you why, okay?

902
00:57:15,200 --> 00:57:16,360
<i>Sure.</i>

903
00:57:17,080 --> 00:57:19,360
Excuse me, that might actually
be him now.

904
00:57:20,360 --> 00:57:21,960
Yes, hello?

905
00:57:33,840 --> 00:57:35,360
Yes, thank you.

906
00:57:37,040 --> 00:57:38,280
That was my office.

907
00:57:38,480 --> 00:57:40,840
There's a woman-
A friend, a relative of yours?

908
00:57:41,040 --> 00:57:43,360
She said she called
on a number you gave her.

909
00:57:44,000 --> 00:57:45,800
She's gonna call back.

910
00:57:52,040 --> 00:57:54,080
<i>-Yes?
-Hi, kiddo.</i>

911
00:57:54,280 --> 00:57:57,280
<i>Listen, your brother Clifford
has just been rushed to the hospital.</i>

912
00:57:57,480 --> 00:57:59,160
<i>He was doing construction
when a thing-</i>

913
00:57:59,360 --> 00:58:01,080
<i>-A steel girder?
-That's it.</i>

914
00:58:01,280 --> 00:58:03,680
<i>You better come to the city
and make your peace with him.</i>

915
00:58:03,880 --> 00:58:05,960
<i>You're booked on the next
flight to San Francisco.</i>

916
00:58:06,160 --> 00:58:08,200
<i>I'm waiting here for you
in front of the terminal.</i>

917
00:58:08,720 --> 00:58:11,000
They reserved me a seat
on the next flight to San Francisco.

918
00:58:11,200 --> 00:58:12,440
-I'll drive you there.
-No, no.

919
00:58:12,640 --> 00:58:15,560
Sharon is waiting at the airport for me.
You can't stand Lanny up.

920
00:58:15,760 --> 00:58:18,120
Please give him
my deepest apologies.

921
00:58:26,760 --> 00:58:29,840
-Hey.
-Please, I can explain.

922
00:58:30,640 --> 00:58:32,840
You've broken the law,
Bonnie-fucking-Trout.

923
00:58:33,040 --> 00:58:34,760
You've assumed
another person's identity...

924
00:58:34,960 --> 00:58:37,240
...to get information
from a business competitor.

925
00:58:37,440 --> 00:58:40,000
Obviously I lied about who I was.
I'm sorry.

926
00:58:40,200 --> 00:58:42,280
It was a huge untruth.
It wasn't planned.

927
00:58:42,480 --> 00:58:46,840
I was just freaked out about
suddenly being on the plane with-

928
00:58:47,840 --> 00:58:49,160
With you...

929
00:58:49,360 --> 00:58:51,560
How did you get the seat
behind me on the plane?

930
00:58:51,720 --> 00:58:53,320
-It was pure coincidence.
-Bullshit!

931
00:58:53,480 --> 00:58:54,880
It's true.

932
00:58:58,760 --> 00:59:02,320
How could you-? How could you have
just left me at the hotel like that?

933
00:59:02,720 --> 00:59:03,880
You were asleep.

934
00:59:04,040 --> 00:59:07,120
Reuben woke me to say
I had to be a substitute performer...

935
00:59:07,320 --> 00:59:11,400
...at a charity concert at the Hollywood
Bowl. I had to get the first flight out.

936
00:59:11,560 --> 00:59:13,080
You could have left a note
or called.

937
00:59:13,280 --> 00:59:15,240
-I did leave you a note.
-Where?

938
00:59:17,040 --> 00:59:20,480
I don't know why we're even talking
about this. I don't like you.

939
00:59:20,680 --> 00:59:23,480
All right? I wish we had never met.

940
00:59:29,120 --> 00:59:30,280
Hello, Vince.

941
00:59:31,000 --> 00:59:32,640
What the fuck's going on?

942
00:59:34,480 --> 00:59:37,040
Vince, a few days after we first met...

943
00:59:37,240 --> 00:59:39,960
...I found myself next to Lanny
on a flight to New York.

944
00:59:40,160 --> 00:59:41,720
It was a complete coincidence.

945
00:59:41,920 --> 00:59:43,520
-He asked my name-
-And she lied.

946
00:59:43,720 --> 00:59:46,840
I had just finished reading the first
chapter of Lanny's own biography.

947
00:59:47,040 --> 00:59:50,280
His lawyers had let me see it in the
hope of discouraging our own project.

948
00:59:50,480 --> 00:59:52,920
As a reflex, since I knew he
would view me as the enemy...

949
00:59:53,120 --> 00:59:54,680
...I gave him the name of a friend...

950
00:59:54,880 --> 00:59:56,880
...whose apartment I was
staying at in Manhattan.

951
00:59:57,080 --> 01:00:00,240
I thought I just had to get through
the awkwardness of the flight itself...

952
01:00:00,440 --> 01:00:02,360
-... but the trouble is-
-You slept with him.

953
01:00:04,160 --> 01:00:07,400
-Vince-
-You slept with my ex-partner.

954
01:00:08,800 --> 01:00:09,960
Technically.

955
01:00:11,920 --> 01:00:14,400
Doesn't sound like things were
particularly technical.

956
01:00:35,320 --> 01:00:37,240
Now, you listen to me, sweetheart.

957
01:00:38,000 --> 01:00:41,760
Vince doesn't always do
what's best for Vince.

958
01:00:41,960 --> 01:00:44,440
That's why he needed me
here today.

959
01:00:45,120 --> 01:00:48,920
The story of this girl is the
most painful thing in his life.

960
01:00:49,120 --> 01:00:51,200
What happened to her, Lanny?

961
01:00:52,320 --> 01:00:54,120
Well, you're not gonna find out.

962
01:00:55,040 --> 01:00:56,520
Not now.

963
01:00:57,240 --> 01:00:59,320
Not after what you've done to him.

964
01:01:08,320 --> 01:01:09,880
Vince.

965
01:01:10,080 --> 01:01:11,320
Oh, shit.

966
01:01:13,200 --> 01:01:15,160
Vince...

967
01:01:15,360 --> 01:01:17,240
...I made a terrible mistake
in New York.

968
01:01:17,440 --> 01:01:20,680
I apologize to you
more than I know how to say.

969
01:01:20,880 --> 01:01:23,000
I'm so sorry.

970
01:01:32,400 --> 01:01:35,560
Vince, the realization
of your life story...

971
01:01:35,760 --> 01:01:38,280
...shouldn't be threatened
because of my failings.

972
01:01:40,400 --> 01:01:43,040
Please let me continue
to work with you again.

973
01:01:44,200 --> 01:01:46,440
I'll help you tell your story right.

974
01:01:48,920 --> 01:01:50,760
Come back tonight.

975
01:01:52,760 --> 01:01:54,360
Let me think about it.

976
01:02:06,480 --> 01:02:10,200
-How do you like the wine?
-It's magnificent. What is it?

977
01:02:10,400 --> 01:02:12,800
1961 Haut-Brion.

978
01:02:13,000 --> 01:02:14,640
People make a big deal of 1959...

979
01:02:14,840 --> 01:02:18,040
...but I don't think there'll be
a year as special as 1961.

980
01:02:18,640 --> 01:02:21,320
It was a great year for French wines.

981
01:02:24,520 --> 01:02:26,360
Will you join me?

982
01:02:27,160 --> 01:02:28,680
What are they?

983
01:02:29,200 --> 01:02:33,200
They're like very mild-mannered
Quaaludes.

984
01:02:33,440 --> 01:02:35,440
Must've done a few of those
in your time, right?

985
01:02:36,880 --> 01:02:38,520
Are you sure they're okay
with alcohol?

986
01:02:38,720 --> 01:02:42,080
Oh, they're even better with alcohol.
Believe me, I'd know.

987
01:02:48,040 --> 01:02:50,080
Come on in, honey. The water's fine.

988
01:02:51,080 --> 01:02:55,720
<i>All my life, I've had this idea
that I could always be in control.</i>

989
01:02:56,320 --> 01:02:58,160
<i>Ever since I was sick,
I had this sense...</i>

990
01:02:58,360 --> 01:03:01,400
<i>...that I could make my body
do anything I wanted.</i>

991
01:03:01,600 --> 01:03:03,200
<i>If I could will my polio away...</i>

992
01:03:03,400 --> 01:03:06,720
<i>...I'd certainly be able to will away
the effect of any drug.</i>

993
01:03:19,880 --> 01:03:23,400
Do you mind if I close the drapes?
The sun's in my eyes.

994
01:03:25,120 --> 01:03:26,920
It's moonlight.

995
01:03:28,280 --> 01:03:29,760
Go ahead.

996
01:04:29,160 --> 01:04:31,120
I remember you.

997
01:04:31,720 --> 01:04:33,360
You're Alice.

998
01:04:34,000 --> 01:04:36,040
In Wonderland.

999
01:04:36,720 --> 01:04:38,840
Oh, I don't know.

1000
01:04:39,040 --> 01:04:41,320
I'm really stoned
out of my head already.

1001
01:04:42,600 --> 01:04:44,080
Is it good?

1002
01:04:49,400 --> 01:04:53,320
Jesus, Vince. It's like monster grass.

1003
01:04:53,520 --> 01:04:55,720
Do you get this stuff all the time?

1004
01:04:55,880 --> 01:04:57,800
All the time.

1005
01:05:06,760 --> 01:05:09,120
You're Alice.

1006
01:05:11,840 --> 01:05:13,440
You're so beautiful.

1007
01:05:41,280 --> 01:05:43,080
She's ours.

1008
01:05:43,760 --> 01:05:45,680
Isn't that so, Alice?

1009
01:05:47,120 --> 01:05:48,920
I'm yours.

1010
01:06:20,840 --> 01:06:22,600
I like you.

1011
01:06:34,760 --> 01:06:37,880
<i>I had always been fascinated by how
some women could cross the line...</i>

1012
01:06:38,080 --> 01:06:42,520
<i>...between who they were and who
they would let themselves become.</i>

1013
01:06:43,200 --> 01:06:44,840
<i>Maureen...</i>

1014
01:06:45,520 --> 01:06:47,280
<i>...Alice...</i>

1015
01:06:47,920 --> 01:06:49,440
<i>...and now...</i>

1016
01:06:49,640 --> 01:06:51,120
<i>...me.</i>

1017
01:06:57,360 --> 01:06:58,640
Morning.

1018
01:06:58,840 --> 01:07:02,000
That was not a Quaalude you
gave me. I've had Quaaludes.

1019
01:07:03,240 --> 01:07:04,520
I said it was like a Quaalude.

1020
01:07:04,720 --> 01:07:07,000
And you didn't take one yourself.
You palmed the pill.

1021
01:07:07,200 --> 01:07:09,120
Somebody had to drive.

1022
01:07:10,040 --> 01:07:11,760
Don't worry, you won't get pregnant.

1023
01:07:11,960 --> 01:07:13,720
Not from Alice,
and certainly not from me.

1024
01:07:13,920 --> 01:07:16,360
I never took off my pants,
as you may or may not remember.

1025
01:07:16,560 --> 01:07:18,160
There are laws against
drugging people.

1026
01:07:18,360 --> 01:07:22,200
Oh, please. You took it voluntarily.
Nobody slipped it into your drink.

1027
01:07:23,720 --> 01:07:26,960
And you chased it with one of the most
expensive wines in the world.

1028
01:07:27,160 --> 01:07:30,440
You're just in a dither because you've
discovered you can swing both ways.

1029
01:07:32,640 --> 01:07:34,400
You see...

1030
01:07:35,400 --> 01:07:37,200
...I needed to get something on you.

1031
01:07:37,400 --> 01:07:40,520
Of course, your behavior with Lanny
might have been even better than this.

1032
01:07:40,720 --> 01:07:42,440
But I'd already set the wheels
in motion.

1033
01:07:42,600 --> 01:07:46,440
And as I was dying to see
you and Alice get it on...

1034
01:07:46,920 --> 01:07:48,960
Well, these are just a sample.

1035
01:07:56,240 --> 01:07:58,960
Why would she agree to do this?
Doesn't she want a career?

1036
01:07:59,160 --> 01:08:01,320
Well, it's your career
I'm worried about.

1037
01:08:01,880 --> 01:08:04,120
You're a journalist
playing loose with the rules.

1038
01:08:04,520 --> 01:08:06,920
She's just a vulnerable young singer
you seduced.

1039
01:08:07,120 --> 01:08:10,040
A promising- Oh, good heavens.

1040
01:08:10,400 --> 01:08:13,000
Promising artist
that I happen to manage.

1041
01:08:13,200 --> 01:08:14,920
You met her through me...

1042
01:08:15,120 --> 01:08:16,960
...and had your way with her.

1043
01:08:21,480 --> 01:08:23,040
What do you want from me?

1044
01:08:25,880 --> 01:08:28,120
You're going to continue
writing the book.

1045
01:08:28,320 --> 01:08:32,040
I'm going to continue telling you
juicy stories, funny stories...

1046
01:08:32,240 --> 01:08:34,240
...heart-tugging stories.

1047
01:08:34,480 --> 01:08:36,640
And you're not going to ask me
a single question...

1048
01:08:36,840 --> 01:08:38,960
...about what happened
to the girl in New Jersey.

1049
01:08:40,040 --> 01:08:42,920
You're going to go to your publisher,
say you tried every angle...

1050
01:08:43,120 --> 01:08:45,960
...but you could find nothing odd
or suspicious in what I told you.

1051
01:08:52,480 --> 01:08:55,240
I'll even try to spice it up a little,
talk about how...

1052
01:08:55,440 --> 01:08:58,280
...the night before the telethon,
I wanted to sleep like a babe...

1053
01:08:58,480 --> 01:09:00,680
...so to cover my bets,
I kept a few babes on hand.

1054
01:09:01,600 --> 01:09:03,080
Well, not exactly on my hand...

1055
01:09:03,280 --> 01:09:06,520
...and that's not my preference,
as you might have gathered by now.

1056
01:09:15,720 --> 01:09:19,440
So you get your bestseller,
I get my million.

1057
01:09:19,640 --> 01:09:20,840
Everyone goes home happy.

1058
01:09:21,040 --> 01:09:24,160
You've dreaded talking about
Maureen O'Flaherty since we met.

1059
01:09:24,360 --> 01:09:26,440
If it's something you're so
desperate to avoid...

1060
01:09:26,600 --> 01:09:28,520
...why would you ever agree
to do this book?

1061
01:09:29,200 --> 01:09:30,800
I need the money.

1062
01:09:31,000 --> 01:09:34,280
Vince, anything you say
in my presence is mine to use.

1063
01:09:35,240 --> 01:09:38,000
Everything you said last night
and everything you've just told me.

1064
01:09:38,200 --> 01:09:40,840
And since I'm also allowed to include
contextual background...

1065
01:09:41,000 --> 01:09:42,960
...I can write about
how you set me up...

1066
01:09:43,160 --> 01:09:46,400
...how you tried to blackmail me.
I'll even include those Polaroids.

1067
01:09:46,600 --> 01:09:49,800
It's your word against mine. We have
a contract. Everything's in my words.

1068
01:09:49,960 --> 01:09:53,160
We've agreed to your answers,
but there's nothing to stop me...

1069
01:09:53,320 --> 01:09:57,840
...from putting any information I want
into a question I ask.

1070
01:09:58,880 --> 01:10:01,720
Information that I'd like to be
public knowledge...

1071
01:10:02,600 --> 01:10:05,000
...or that the police
might wanna look into.

1072
01:10:09,440 --> 01:10:13,600
Would you like me to fire one of my
loaded questions, on the record?

1073
01:10:14,440 --> 01:10:16,120
Sure.

1074
01:10:22,920 --> 01:10:24,800
Vince...

1075
01:10:25,320 --> 01:10:28,600
...in your suite
at the Versailles Hotel in Miami...

1076
01:10:29,240 --> 01:10:31,520
...was it your or Lanny's idea...

1077
01:10:31,720 --> 01:10:34,920
...to put Maureen's body into the case
containing shellfish and ice...

1078
01:10:35,080 --> 01:10:36,680
...and have it shipped
to New Jersey?

1079
01:10:41,360 --> 01:10:44,120
No answer, Mr. Collins?
So noted.

1080
01:10:44,720 --> 01:10:47,480
Oh, and incidentally,
by not answering...

1081
01:10:47,680 --> 01:10:50,160
...you're in violation of your contract.

1082
01:10:50,760 --> 01:10:53,800
What a shame.
I understood you needed that money.

1083
01:11:07,920 --> 01:11:10,000
Oh, no. Oh, God.

1084
01:11:10,200 --> 01:11:13,760
Oh, God.
Oh, God. Oh, God!

1085
01:11:22,160 --> 01:11:23,880
Was that how
you murdered Maureen?

1086
01:11:36,760 --> 01:11:38,520
Ask Lanny.

1087
01:11:41,160 --> 01:11:43,120
He's the one who knows.

1088
01:12:00,840 --> 01:12:04,400
<i>It wasn't that hard for him
to get the suite he wanted.</i>

1089
01:12:04,600 --> 01:12:08,440
<i>The Versailles was still one of the
fanciest of the hotels along the beach.</i>

1090
01:12:08,640 --> 01:12:11,200
<i>But by then, its era had passed.</i>

1091
01:12:12,520 --> 01:12:14,080
Thank you, sir.

1092
01:12:23,120 --> 01:12:25,360
<i>All the furniture was new.</i>

1093
01:12:25,600 --> 01:12:27,840
<i>It had been 15 years...</i>

1094
01:12:28,520 --> 01:12:30,400
<i>...but the floor plan...</i>

1095
01:12:30,600 --> 01:12:32,680
<i>...was still the same.</i>

1096
01:12:33,480 --> 01:12:35,600
<i>In that spot...</i>

1097
01:12:35,920 --> 01:12:38,720
<i>...that was where the truth
had come out.</i>

1098
01:12:39,720 --> 01:12:42,400
<i>That was why she had to die.</i>

1099
01:12:52,800 --> 01:12:55,240
Are you Japanese or Chinese?

1100
01:12:56,440 --> 01:12:58,080
Vietnamese.

1101
01:12:58,520 --> 01:13:01,640
The kitchen tell me
you famous person.

1102
01:13:01,840 --> 01:13:03,720
Why you famous?

1103
01:13:04,040 --> 01:13:06,080
They didn't tell you my name?

1104
01:13:06,280 --> 01:13:07,440
No.

1105
01:13:07,640 --> 01:13:09,280
What is it?

1106
01:13:11,560 --> 01:13:13,240
Lanny Morris.

1107
01:13:13,960 --> 01:13:15,560
It's a Jewish name...

1108
01:13:15,720 --> 01:13:17,160
...but I'm a nebbish.

1109
01:13:18,360 --> 01:13:20,680
You ordered three bottle
of champagne.

1110
01:13:20,880 --> 01:13:22,120
You want me to open one now?

1111
01:13:22,760 --> 01:13:24,720
Or wait until friend come?

1112
01:13:25,800 --> 01:13:27,240
Open all three.

1113
01:13:28,840 --> 01:13:31,040
Are you really famous, Mr. Morris?

1114
01:13:32,200 --> 01:13:33,760
In my day.

1115
01:13:34,200 --> 01:13:36,160
Before your time, I suppose.

1116
01:13:37,160 --> 01:13:39,600
I come from the north of Vietnam.

1117
01:13:39,800 --> 01:13:42,040
In my town, there is no television.

1118
01:13:42,240 --> 01:13:46,360
<i>She explained that American movies
had been banned where she grew up.</i>

1119
01:13:51,400 --> 01:13:53,960
<i>She got better tips pretending
she was Madame Butterfly...</i>

1120
01:13:54,120 --> 01:13:57,080
<i>...than by telling people
where she was really from.</i>

1121
01:13:58,160 --> 01:14:00,160
What did you do, Mr. Morris?

1122
01:14:01,200 --> 01:14:03,640
I made Vince Collins' life...

1123
01:14:04,040 --> 01:14:06,080
...very difficult.

1124
01:14:06,280 --> 01:14:09,320
<i>She didn't understand, but her policy
was not to linger in the rooms...</i>

1125
01:14:09,520 --> 01:14:11,400
<i>...of solitary gentlemen.</i>

1126
01:14:12,720 --> 01:14:16,840
<i>He signed the room-service check
under Lanny's name.</i>

1127
01:14:19,000 --> 01:14:20,480
Thank you.

1128
01:14:42,600 --> 01:14:44,760
<i>There was no ice or water
left in the buckets...</i>

1129
01:14:44,960 --> 01:14:47,640
<i>...when his body was discovered
the next morning.</i>

1130
01:14:48,840 --> 01:14:52,440
<i>He had dumped the ice into
the bathtub and died in it.</i>

1131
01:14:53,640 --> 01:14:56,600
<i>He must have felt
there was some poetry in it.</i>

1132
01:14:59,880 --> 01:15:02,120
<i>His plan was to drink
enough champagne...</i>

1133
01:15:02,320 --> 01:15:03,680
<i>...with enough sleeping pills...</i>

1134
01:15:03,880 --> 01:15:07,600
<i>...so that ending things would
become an acceptable idea.</i>

1135
01:15:08,320 --> 01:15:10,120
<i>He could manage that.</i>

1136
01:15:10,920 --> 01:15:14,120
<i>He knew for certain
he couldn't manage anything else.</i>

1137
01:15:17,520 --> 01:15:19,040
Hi.

1138
01:15:21,200 --> 01:15:23,800
I thought you were
gonna be out all afternoon.

1139
01:15:28,360 --> 01:15:30,040
I'm sorry.

1140
01:15:30,440 --> 01:15:32,240
It's okay.

1141
01:15:33,160 --> 01:15:35,120
This was under the door.

1142
01:15:42,400 --> 01:15:43,600
What is it?

1143
01:15:45,160 --> 01:15:47,200
Chapter three.

1144
01:15:48,920 --> 01:15:53,040
<i>John, as my lawyer, I want you
to know that this next chapter...</i>

1145
01:15:53,240 --> 01:15:56,080
<i>...is to be read
after Vince and my death...</i>

1146
01:15:56,280 --> 01:16:00,760
<i>...and is only to be used under
the most extreme of circumstances.</i>

1147
01:16:02,400 --> 01:16:04,400
<i>We knew we wanted to make
an early night of it...</i>

1148
01:16:04,600 --> 01:16:07,880
<i>...with the telethon starting the next
day, so Vince suggested we dine in...</i>

1149
01:16:08,080 --> 01:16:10,960
<i>...so Maureen could do
the interview for her campus paper.</i>

1150
01:16:11,160 --> 01:16:15,960
This is a gift for us
from the audience...

1151
01:16:16,560 --> 01:16:20,360
...from the people,
the people that are out there.

1152
01:16:21,160 --> 01:16:25,240
Sooner or later you gotta say,
"We wanna give something back. "

1153
01:16:25,480 --> 01:16:27,040
I think that's really important.

1154
01:16:27,240 --> 01:16:31,360
Not many people would take
the time out to do that. Thank you.

1155
01:16:31,560 --> 01:16:34,160
<i>She actually hid her tape recorder
in the room-service cart...</i>

1156
01:16:34,360 --> 01:16:37,000
<i>...because she didn't want
the hotel to find out.</i>

1157
01:16:44,520 --> 01:16:47,600
<i>We finished the interview
and then asked her to stay.</i>

1158
01:16:50,560 --> 01:16:54,440
<i>To help us get into the mood,
I did a Tuinal...</i>

1159
01:16:54,640 --> 01:16:56,200
